Hypotheses

It can be helpful to think about your research question and hypotheses before data analysis

  • I hypothesize that species with [insert life history characteristic] will have longer petals than species that do not

  • If so, I would expect:

  • If not, I would expect to see:

Boxplot

Graph Gallery: Boxplots in ggplot2

library(ggplot2)
g1 <- ggplot(iris, aes(x=as.factor(Species), y=Petal.Length)) + 
  geom_boxplot(fill="slateblue", alpha=0.2) 

g1

Incorporate Color

g1 <- ggplot(iris, aes(x=as.factor(Species), y=Petal.Length)) + 
    geom_boxplot(fill="slateblue", alpha=0.2) 

g2 <- ggplot(iris, aes(x=as.factor(Species),
y=Petal.Length, 
fill=Species)) + 
    geom_boxplot() 

g2

Change color palette

library(viridis)
## Loading required package: viridisLite
g2 <- g2 + 
  scale_fill_viridis(discrete=T)

g2

Relabel Axes

Choose human-friendly axis labels

g2 <- g2 + 
  xlab("Species") + 
  ylab("Petal Length (cm)")

g2

Using color-brewer to choose colors

ColorBrewer

palette  <- c("#1b9e77", 
              "#d95f02",
              "#7570b3")

mycolors <- c("I. setosa" = palette[1],
"I. versicolor" = palette[2], 
"I. virginica" = palette[3])

Rename species

library(dplyr)
## 
## Attaching package: 'dplyr'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     filter, lag
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
iris$Species <- recode(iris$Species, setosa = "I. setosa", 
versicolor = "I. versicolor",
virginica = "I. virginica")

Incorporate colors

g3 <- ggplot(iris, aes(x=as.factor(Species),
y=Petal.Length,fill=Species)) + geom_boxplot() + scale_fill_manual(
  values=c("I. setosa" = palette[1],
"I. versicolor" = palette[2], 
"I. virginica" = palette[3]))+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(face = "italic"),
        legend.text = element_text(face="italic")) +
  xlab("Species") + ylab("Petal Length (cm)")

g3

Increase font size!

g3 <- g3 + theme(axis.title = element_text(size = 20)) 

g3

Saving your figures-1

Straight from RStudio

You can export your figure straight from RStudio:

Save as pdf

  • This saves your figure as a pdf within your working directory.

  • Warning: Some Mac/PC compatability issues

pdf("my_figure.pdf", width=6.5,
    height=6.5, pointsize=8,
    encoding="TeXtext.enc", onefile=F)
g1
dev.off()
## quartz_off_screen 
##                 2

Save as png

  • This saves your figure as a .png file in your working directory.
png("my_figure.png", width=6.5,
    height=8, pointsize=8,
units="in", res=300)
g3
dev.off()
## quartz_off_screen 
##                 2

Some figure tips

  • I recommend keeping all code to run figures in a separate script.

  • After running analyses, save dataframe as a csv which can be loaded at top of figure script

  • Dont be ashamed to Google how to do things

-Best practices for visualization concepts and presentation strategies- J. R. Carey: An hour-long presentation on putting together talks
